n rural India -- tBuilding alternative communities within the state: the Kurdish Movement, local municipalities and democratic autonomy -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis edited collection critically explores the funding arrangements governing contemporary community development and how they shape its theory and practice. International contributions from activists, practitioners and academics consider the evolution of funding in community development and how changes in policy and practice can be understood in relation to the politics of neoliberalism and contemporary efforts to build global democracy from the ‘bottom up’. Thematically, the collection explores matters such as popular democracy, the shifting contours of the state-market relationship, prospects for democratising the state, the feasibility of community autonomy, the effects of managerialism and hybrid modes of funding such as social finance. The collection is thus uniquely positioned to stimulate critical debate on both policy and practice within the broad field of community development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aCommunity developmentxFinance. 0aCommunity developmentxPolitical aspects. 0aPower (Social sciences). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aBalazard, Hélène, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanks, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBender, Lin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinnegan, Fergal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinnegan, Fergal, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFisher, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlader, Ul